I just passed by Yayoi Kusama in San Francisco!  I'm really not sure if she got her hands on this, but I know it's from hers!

Yayoi Kusama (草間 彌生, Kusama Yayoi, born 22 March 1929) is a Japanese contemporary artist who works primarily in sculpture and installation, and is also active in painting, performance, video art, fashion, poetry, fiction, and other arts. Her work is based in conceptual art and shows some attributes of feminism, minimalism, surrealism, Art Brut, pop art, and abstract expressionism, and is infused with autobiographical, psychological, and sexual content. She has been acknowledged as one of the most important living artists to come out of Japan,[1] the world's top-selling female artist,[2] and the world's most successful living artist.[3] Her work influenced that of her contemporaries, including Andy Warhol and Claes Oldenburg.

…after almost 10 years we decided to rescue our old art studio in Miami Beach!  The container crossed the country by train and everything arrived intact!  During the next few days we will be busy remembering and inventorying all these good memories and materials! Today those memories are incorporated into my story and available at MOCOTOPIA California!

I'm taking the colorful books off the shelf, the cute ones, the ones that focus on beauty, the ones that once enchanted…. Well, I heard an opinion that it's tacky to consume art like that! Now it is the turn of the grotesque, the ugliness, the laceration, the politics, the segregation of races and genders…. I don't know, but I think that even if I force myself I can't, my soul doesn't exist to illuminate these things! I'm part of the team that is out of fashion, I still worship beauty, harmony, laughter, celebration, pride and cheerful colors! In fact, I took the books off the shelf to revisit them and reinforce my conviction that only beauty saves! ❤️💐

R.I.P Fernando Botero
“That’s what makes an artist a true artist: the passion and love he has for his craft and the desire to pursue it every day of his life.” 

Fernando Botero Angulo (19 April 1932 – 15 September 2023) was a Colombian figurative artist and sculptor, born in Medellín. His characteristic style, also known as “Boterism”, depicts people and figures in large, exaggerated volumes, which can represent political criticism or humor, depending on the piece. He is considered the most recognized and cited living artist in Latin America, and his art can be found in highly visible places around the world, such as Park Avenue in New York and Champs- Élysées in Paris.

My artistic discourse sometimes follows some shortcuts, sometimes I also test to know how I am seen by art critics and whether my purpose follows a genuine line in people's perception! Yes, I worry about that! Since the beginning of my career as a painter, my paintings have demonstrated a certain nostalgia, as a contemporary version of past styles! For example, I try to create Renaissance and Victorian motifs in a contemporary style, in an attempt to give more lightness and make everyone want the joy that my paintings convey! I like to feel like a renewer, presenting my version of the aesthetic senses to the world! I am aware of some stereotypes and classifications that people give me, especially those who do not follow the evolution of my intentions and who have never had the opportunity to enter the door of my art studio! I found some pieces of a set used in an old theater of San Francisco, a treasure that dates back almost 100 years and that will serve as an intervention for my inspirations, strengthening my concept!

#mocotopia #moco #mocó #contemporaryart #contemporarypainting #califonianartist #victorian #beniciacalifornia

My fascination has always been recreating good memories through art! Reproducing contemporary elements that convey transcendence is a great challenge, as I can’t always capture this “strength”, as I don’t even know where it comes from or where it is! I try not to condition my artistic production to these moments of epiphany, but when this “force” arrives, I inevitably produce with a lot of passion!

Why share this? It’s part of my artistic project to reuse objects that have already provoked some type of emotion, an emotion when decorating a family home, like a new style, a new sensation, a novelty, a new vibe! I prefer decorative objects, because I know that in the past an action of love was provoked there, a gesture of surprise and expectation! I like to imagine the satisfaction the previous owners had when purchasing it and the surprise it caused. These objects, for me, are imbued with many emotions and I want to continue these feelings, integrating them into my art and rekindling that little moment of joy! I still cultivate the habit of contemplating objects and trying to guess everything that has happened around them! I like to rescue emotions and continue the joy!
